05582nam a22007695i 9780857453198DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574531987 a10.1515/97808574531982doi  a(DE-B1597)636520  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGN25 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a30100aHolistic Anthropology :bEmergence and Convergence /ced. by David Parkin, Stanley Ulijaszek. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMethodology & History in Anthropology ;v1600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of figures and tables -- tList of contributors -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: emergence and convergence -- t1. Bioculturalism -- t2. The biological in the social: evolutionary approaches to human behaviour -- t3. Domesticating the landscape, producing crops and reproducing society in Amazonia -- t4. The biological in the cultural: the five agents and the body ecologic in Chinese medicine -- t5. On the social, the biological and the political: revisiting Beatrice Blackwood’s research and teaching -- t6. Anthropological theory and the multiple determinacy of the present -- t7. Holism, intelligence and time -- t8. Movement, knowledge and description -- t9. The evolution and history of religion -- t10. The visceral in the social: the crowd as paradigmatic type -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGiven the broad reach of anthropology as the science of humankind, there are times when the subject fragments into specialisms and times when there is rapprochement. Rather than just seeing them as reactions to each other, it is perhaps better to say that both tendencies co-exist and that it is very much a matter of perspective as to which is dominant at any moment. The perspective adopted by the contributors to this volume is that some anthropologists have, over the last decade or so, been paying considerable attention to developments in the study of social and biological evolution and of material culture, and that this has brought social, material cultural and biological anthropologists closer to each other and closer to allied disciplines such as archaeology and psychology. A more eclectic anthropology once characteristic of an earlier age is thus re-emerging. The new holism does not result from the merging of sharply distinguished disciplines but from among anthropologists themselves who see social organization as fundamentally a problem of human ecology, and, from that, of material and mental creativity, human biology, and the co-evolution of society and culture. It is part of a wider interest beyond anthropology in the origins and rationale of human activities, claims and beliefs, and draws on inferential or speculative reasoning as well as ‘hard’ evidence. The book argues that, while usefully borrowing from other subjects, all such reasoning must be grounded in prolonged, intensive and linguistically-informed fieldwork and comparison.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aAnthropology. 0aHolism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aDunbar, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGosden, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsu, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngold, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorphy, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParkin, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParkin, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/